BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Chicago Poet Laureate Mayda Del Valle joins Chicago's Late Night T
 alk Show
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260318T193000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260318T210000
UID:260312VfSik7uk80OrP7pszifXdg
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/DGcUz5ofTku1UOfY_xiLgg.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Get the late night talk show experience without heading to NYC
  or LA!\n\nThe Not That Late Show is a POC- and queer-led late-night talk 
 show hosted by Justin Swinson\, featuring an ensemble of Chicago comedians
  debuting brand-new material each month. NTLS is just like the late night 
 talk shows you would see on TV \\(Colbert\, The Daily Show\, Last Week Ton
 ight\, etc.\\)\, but with a Chicago focus. Taking place every third Wednes
 day at The Lincoln Lodge\, the show blends sketch comedy\, sharp interview
 s\, and live music from emerging local artists. Past guests have included 
 Mayor Brandon Johnson\; Writer and Educator Dr. Eve L. Ewing\; Viral Chica
 go Attorney\, Rachel Cohen\; and Medea Benjamin of CODEPINK among others.\
 n\nThis month we'll be joined by Chicago Poet Laureate\, Mayda Del Valle.
LOCATION:The Lincoln Lodge
URL:https://evanstonroundtable.com/events/#/details/chicago-poet-laureate-
 mayda-del-valle-joins-chicago-s-late-night-talk-show/18315355/2026-03-18T1
 9
X-SOURCE:Evanston Roundtable
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Reading the Cards: A Tarot Study Group
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260318T180000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260318T193000
UID:260309zCM-G5k-FEOCQAKbfmAX3A
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/PEgP9xeE1ESFUr4NxaAmqQ.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Picking up a tarot deck for the first time can feel overwhelmi
 ng. Seventy-eight cards\, all that symbolism\, and no idea where to begin.
  The good news? You don't need to memorize anything to start reading. You 
 just need a little guidance and a willingness to look closely at what's in
  front of you.\n\nIn this hands-on workshop\, participants will use Stefa
 nie Caponi's Guided Tarot as a roadmap to start reading cards with confide
 nce. Rather than memorizing textbook definitions\, we'll explore exercises
  from the book that help you develop your own relationship with the cards 
 using intuition\, observation\, and storytelling.\n\nThe box set includes 
 a Rider Waite Smith deck\, which is the foundation most modern tarot decks
  are built on. Learning with this deck gives you a visual language that tr
 ansfers to nearly any other deck you pick up down the road\, making it an 
 especially smart starting point for anyone planning to continue learning o
 r take future workshops.\n\nYou'll leave with practical skills you can use
  immediately: how to do a simple reading for yourself\, how to interpret w
 hat you see \\(not just what you've been told a card means\\)\, and a fram
 ework for continued practice at home.\n\nNo experience necessary. You don'
 t need to "believe" in anything\, just bring your curiosity.
LOCATION:Bookends & Beginnings
URL:https://evanstonroundtable.com/events/#/details/reading-the-cards-a-ta
 rot-study-group/18280895/2026-03-18T18
X-SOURCE:Evanston Roundtable
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:March Blue Hour Featuring April Gibson and Mira Cameron
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260318T190000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260318T203000
UID:260302E0zfawSZqE27MEzTtcxesQ
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/5xdm37torkKgsQtEJJ7jWA.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:The Chicago Poetry Center presents BLUE HOUR\, a free monthly 
 in-person reading series and generative writing workshop. Our March featur
 ed readers are April Gibson and Mira Cameron.\n\nEach event takes place at
  Haymarket House \\(800 W. Buena\\) and includes a brief open mic followed
  by two featured poets. Pre-registration is free and recommended. The open
  mic includes five readers drawn lottery-style from a hat that goes out at
  7:15. The reading starts promptly at 7:30. Each open mic poet reads one p
 oem or for three minutes\, whichever comes first.\n\nEVENT DETAILS FOR Mar
 ch 18:\n\nWorkshop \\(registration required\\) begins promptly at 6 p.m.\,
  ends at 7 p.m.\n\nPerformance space doors open and open mic sign-up begin
 s at 7 p.m.\n\nReading \\(registration recommended but not required\\) beg
 ins at 7:30\, followed by community gathering time.\n\nReading registratio
 n is free\; the workshop is sliding scale with a suggested donation of $10
 .\n\nABOUT THE READING: \n\nThe Blue Hour reading features readings by two
  poets from Chicago and beyond\, preceded by a five person lottery-style o
 pen mic and followed by community gathering time. \n\nABOUT THE WORKSHOP:
  \n\nThe Blue Hour generative writing workshop is suitable for writers and
  poetry fans of all levels. We will discuss a poem together\, then Marty w
 ill guide the group through individual writing on an exploratory prompt th
 at draws on themes from the poem. \n\nABOUT THE SPACE:\n\nAccessibility\,
  Health\, & Safety:\n\n– All restrooms at Haymarket House are gender-neu
 tral\, including single-user and stalled restrooms.\n\n– Each event incl
 udes ASL interpretation. Haymarket House is ADA compliant and fully wheelc
 hair-accessible\; email curator@poetrycenter.org to ensure ramp access and
  with any other accessibility needs.\n\n– Masks are strongly encouraged 
 for all indoor events\, and the space is equipped with a professional air 
 filtration system.\n\nMARCH FEATURES: \n\nApril Gibson is a poet\, writer\
 , and professor whose work has appeared in The Kenyon Review\, Michigan Qu
 arterly Review\, Rhino\, Prairie Schooner and elsewhere. Her poetry collec
 tion\, "The Span of a Small Forever" \\(Amistad/HarperCollins\, 2024\\) wa
 s shortlisted for a Chicago Review of Books Award and first runner-up for 
 Chicago Reader’s Best of Chicago. April is a recipient of The Gwendolyn 
 Brooks Poetry Award\, and she has received grants\, fellowships\, or resid
 encies from the Poetry Foundation\, Tin House\, Callaloo\, Vermont Studio 
 Center\, the National Endowment for the Humanities and others. April is an
  Assistant Professor of English at Malcolm X College.\n\nMira Cameron is a
  girl helping create\, maybe anarchy\, or a phantasia\, or a group of tran
 s people holding hands. She is playing in warm dirt and trying to feed as 
 many as she can\, or otherwise\, editing the poetry section of Imposter.\n
 \nABOUT THE HOST: \n\nMarty McConnell is a poet\, educator\, and healer b
 ased in Chicago. She is the author of when they say you can’t go home a
 gain\, what they mean is you were never there\, winner of the 2017 Michael
  Waters Poetry Prize\; her first full-length collection\, wine for a shot
 gun\, received the Silver Medal in the Independent Publishers Awards and w
 as a finalist for both the Audre Lorde Award and a Lambda Literary Award. 
 Her first nonfiction book\, Gathering Voices: Creating a Community-Based 
 Poetry Workshop\, is available through YesYes Books. She is the co-creato
 r and co-editor of underbelly\, a web site focused on the art and magic o
 f poetry revision. An MFA graduate of Sarah Lawrence College\, her work ha
 s appeared in numerous journals and anthologies including Best American P
 oetry\, Southern Humanities Review\, Gulf Coast\, and Indiana Review.
LOCATION:Haymarket House
URL:https://www.poetrycenter.org/event/blue-hour-april-gibson-mira-cameron
 /
X-SOURCE:Evanston Roundtable
END:VEVENT
