BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Adventures of Huckleberry Finn: Mark Twain's Magnificent Failure (
 Hybrid)
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260318T100000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260318T113000
UID:260227lxN96fw5gkO7VHzTTwhvTw
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/c9sq_yPuVkG4cKqDPaZdDA.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Adventures of Huckleberry Finn is a novel about escape: from 
 slavery\, from abusive family life\, and from an oppressive culture. It is
  a work of comic satire\, and a critique of a warped society that allows s
 ome people to enslave others. Shortly after its publication\, the book was
  proclaimed a classic. However\, critics often suggest that Twain’s fail
 ure of nerve in the final ten chapters keeps the work from developing it
 s most crucial theme and being the great American novel it might have been
 . Jerry Leitner examines what is right and wrong with Mark Twain’s most 
 familiar and significant writing.
LOCATION:North Shore Senior Center
URL:http://www.nssc.org
X-SOURCE:Evanston Roundtable
END:VEVENT
