BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Talks@EHC: Blanche Gildin & the Foundations of an Artistic Practic
 e
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260324T183000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260324T183000
UID:260203XB1ia8vBd0CO5WPakIix-g
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/qqb_9spmE0uk1inK1kVdRg.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Blanche Gildin (1928-2024) was an Evanston-based artist whose 
 studies at Chicago’s Institute of Design from 1947 to 1949 shaped her ar
 tistic practice across more than seven decades. Like many women artists of
  her generation\, she worked in private\, guided less by recognition than 
 by curiosity and discipline. Dr. Lara Allison from the School of the Art I
 nstitute of Chicago and author of the just-published catalog *Blanche Gild
 in: Back to the Bauhaus* will discuss Gildin\, her work\, and the New Bauh
 aus movement at the Institute of Design with the artist's daughter\, Bonny
  Gildin and Jack Weiss of Design Evanston\, who also studied at the Instit
 ute of Design. Three of Gildin's works–recently accessioned into the Eva
 nston History Center's permanent art collection–will be on view. FREE\, 
 please RSVP
LOCATION:Evanston History Center
URL:https://evanstonhistorycenter.org/event/talksehc-blanche-gildin-the-ba
 uhaus-in-chicago-and-the-foundations-of-an-artistic-practice/
X-SOURCE:Evanston Roundtable
END:VEVENT
