BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:TEXAS ART NOW: Rhythms and Myths
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260401T090000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260401T160000
UID:260312JGwL7jPawEuaBkybyo84Tw
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/4MuPqT7cgUmq5A888oIt7w.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:The Evanston Art Center \\(EAC\\) is excited to welcome the pu
 blic to our upcoming exhibition\, TEXAS ART NOW: Rhythms and Myths. The ex
 hibition will be on display from March 28 - April 19\, 2026\, with an open
 ing reception on Sunday\, March 29\, from 1-4pm that will be free and open
  to the public.\n\nAll four artists\, Michael Roqué Collins\, Sherry Owen
 s\, Carlos Canul\, and Sharon Kopriva presented in TEXAS ART NOW: Rhythms 
 and Myths explore and create their complementary subjects showing views wi
 th essential senses of mystery\, memory\, and dreams within natural and hu
 man horizons. Their creative efforts exploring the natural world are fille
 d with interpretations of the inherent mysteries and rhythms that amplify 
 the subconscious realm making these combinations of art a most powerful ex
 hibition.
LOCATION:Evanston Art Center
URL:https://www.evanstonartcenter.org/exhibitions/texas-art-now-rhythms-an
 d-myths
X-SOURCE:Evanston Roundtable
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Jibaritos Chicago Celebrates 10 Years of Authentic Puerto Rican Fl
 avor
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260401T070000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260401T120000
UID:260309EVM6nqCel0WxXATokVm2EA
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/m57DZu8vWU6hOmvYB4fmgg.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:This April 1st marks the 10th anniversary of Jibaritos y Más\
 , the beloved Chicago Puerto Rican restaurant known for its signature jiba
 rito sandwich and rich Latin flavors that has since grown to three Chicago
  locations. Since opening its doors in 2016\, the family-owned business ha
 s become a local culinary staple\, delighting generations of diners and ce
 lebrating Puerto Rican food culture throughout the city. In celebration of
  the anniversary\, free jibaritos will be available from 7am until 12pm a
 t their 3400 West Fullerton location in honor of the 10-year anniversary.
  \n\nFounded a decade ago by Yelitza Rivera\, a Venezuelan native with n
 early 20 years of experience cooking in Puerto Rican kitchens\, Jibaritos
  y Más began as a modest corner spot in Logan Square. Rivera’s deep ro
 ots in Latin cooking and her connection to the community helped turn her v
 ision into reality\, serving authentic\, freshly prepared dishes inspired 
 by traditional Puerto Rican and Latin American cuisine.\n\nRivera’s son\
 , Jesus Arrieta\, joined the venture early on\, working alongside his mot
 her to grow the brand and deepen the business’s community impact. Togeth
 er\, they nurtured the restaurant from its original location into a thrivi
 ng local favorite\, known for its flavorful jibarito sandwiches which are 
 a Chicago-born creation featuring crispy fried green plantains in place of
  bread.\n\nOver the past decade\, Jibaritos y Más expanded into three v
 ibrant Chicago neighborhoods: Logan Square\, Harlem Avenue\, and Archer Av
 enue\, bringing its unique blend of tradition and innovation to diners acr
 oss the city:\n\nJibaritos y Más \\(Logan Square\\) – The original loc
 ation that started it all.\n\nJibaritos on Harlem – A community-favorit
 e spot on Chicago’s northwest side.\n\nJibaritos y Más Southside – W
 elcoming guests with Puerto Rican classics on the South Side.\n\nWhat bega
 n as a single storefront has grown into a Chicago institution where locals
  and visitors alike gather to enjoy hearty jibaritos\, savory lechón asad
 o\, ropa vieja\, yuca fries\, and more\, all while experiencing the warmth
  of family-driven hospitality. The jibarito is a true Chicago original\, c
 reated within the city’s Puerto Rican community in the 1990s and inspire
 d by the Caribbean patacón\, a twice-fried green plantain traditionally e
 njoyed in Puerto Rico and across Latin America\, including Maracaibo. Chic
 ago cooks transformed the patacón into a sandwich by replacing bread with
  crispy green plantains and filling it with steak\, garlic\, lettuce\, tom
 ato\, and mayo. Through Jibaritos y Más\, the jibarito was elevated from
  a neighborhood favorite to a citywide staple\, served consistently\, auth
 entically\, and at scale to generations of Chicagoans.\n\n“We are incred
 ibly proud to celebrate ten years of serving our Chicago community\,” sa
 id Yelitza Rivera. “This journey has been about more than great food. It
 ’s about sharing our culture\, our traditions\, and making everyone who 
 walks through our doors feel like family.” Added Arrieta\, “We are so 
 grateful for our loyal following\, and they all truly feel like family to 
 us. It is our honor to play a part in some big events in their lives throu
 gh our catering\, from graduations to weddings to birthdays to anniversari
 es.”   \n\nAs Jibaritos Chicago marks this milestone\, the team rema
 ins committed to preserving authentic Latin flavors while continuing to in
 novate and delight customers with fresh menu offerings and community-cente
 red experiences.\n\nJibaritos Chicago also specializes in providing exquis
 ite catering services for a wide range of events. Whether it's a corporate
  gathering\, a wedding\, or a private celebration\, they are dedicated to 
 delivering an exceptional culinary experience that will impress\, offering
  customizable menus and professional service.\n\nFor more information\, vi
 sit jibaritoschicago.com and follow Jibaritos Chicago on social media to
  join in the anniversary celebrations throughout April.
LOCATION:Jibaritos y Más
URL:https://www.jibaritoschicago.com/
X-SOURCE:Evanston Roundtable
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Graceful Giraffes: Africa's Long-Neck Wonders (Hybrid)
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260401T140000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260401T153000
UID:260309BzzSv0BCVEuZ-D7t4jY4xQ
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/rz4Lz9bLC0uE_01nfu-9Fg.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:The tallest of all land mammals\, giraffes can eat foliage up 
 to 20 feet off the ground. These nonterritorial herbivores may live in gro
 ups of up to 20. Although these gentle giants have fascinated humans since
  ancient Egyptian times\, they are now vulnerable to extinction. John Ulfe
 rt will focus on the giraffe’s unique anatomy\, habitat\, social life\, 
 parenting\, and conservation status. Be amazed at the original photographs
  of giraffes from John's extensive travels in Africa.
LOCATION:North Shore Senior Center
URL:http://www.nssc.org
X-SOURCE:Evanston Roundtable
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:The U.S. Supreme Court (Hybrid)
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260401T100000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260401T113000
UID:260309AQ5iInsCj0uwKCgvDdidWQ
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/DzGQ0kFmnk2zJwjJw7ZiAA.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:The United States is supposed to have three co-equal branches 
 of government. However\, only 8.25% of the words in the Constitution deal 
 with the judiciary branch. The Supreme Court that we know today has been c
 reated by the efforts of past Chief Justices\, principally John Marshall\,
  and the landmark 1803 Marbury vs. Madison decision. Gary Midkiff focuses 
 on the history and political dalliances of the Court\, including the 1857 
 Dred Scott decision\, the 1896 Plessy vs. Ferguson decision\, the 1954 Bro
 wn vs. Board of Education\, and the 2010 Citizens United decision.
LOCATION:North Shore Senior Center
URL:http://www.nssc.org
X-SOURCE:Evanston Roundtable
END:VEVENT
