BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:TEXAS ART NOW: Rhythms and Myths
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260406T090000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260406T160000
UID:260312uAK7WUarekG6-b--H37_xQ
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/4MuPqT7cgUmq5A888oIt7w.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:The Evanston Art Center \\(EAC\\) is excited to welcome the pu
 blic to our upcoming exhibition\, TEXAS ART NOW: Rhythms and Myths. The ex
 hibition will be on display from March 28 - April 19\, 2026\, with an open
 ing reception on Sunday\, March 29\, from 1-4pm that will be free and open
  to the public.\n\nAll four artists\, Michael Roqué Collins\, Sherry Owen
 s\, Carlos Canul\, and Sharon Kopriva presented in TEXAS ART NOW: Rhythms 
 and Myths explore and create their complementary subjects showing views wi
 th essential senses of mystery\, memory\, and dreams within natural and hu
 man horizons. Their creative efforts exploring the natural world are fille
 d with interpretations of the inherent mysteries and rhythms that amplify 
 the subconscious realm making these combinations of art a most powerful ex
 hibition.
LOCATION:Evanston Art Center
URL:https://www.evanstonartcenter.org/exhibitions/texas-art-now-rhythms-an
 d-myths
X-SOURCE:Evanston Roundtable
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Why is Football Called Soccer?: History of Most Popular Sport in t
 he World
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260406T130000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260406T143000
UID:260309fHc2U2UGYEmdORNNpzrPrQ
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/1nEErQYS8UmXWdBeYxRbQA.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:The biggest sporting event in the world\, the men's World Cup 
 of Football is taking place in North America in the summer of 2026. From i
 ts origins in England to its present global popularity\, John Lyons discus
 ses the history of football\, referred to as soccer in the U.S. Using movi
 e clips\, photos\, and newspaper reports from around the world\, he prov
 ides a great preview to this exciting upcoming event.
LOCATION:North Shore Senior Center
URL:http://www.nssc.org
X-SOURCE:Evanston Roundtable
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Conscription\, Race\, and Citizenship in The Civil War (Hybrid)
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260406T100000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260406T113000
UID:260309BP8qQH2Ahk2m2RCR2DF2vQ
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/R4u9kfffTk22mwuQ46nHcQ.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Demand for troops forced both the Union and Confederacy to aba
 ndon Americans' antipathy toward compulsory military service. Joseph Harri
 ngton explains how joining the ranks\, on a voluntary or compulsory basis
 \, established the prospect of full citizenship for African Americans and 
 immigrants.This action was not without violent resistance to conscription\
 , most notably in the infamous New York City Draft Riot of July 1863.
LOCATION:North Shore Senior Center
URL:http://www.nssc.org
X-SOURCE:Evanston Roundtable
END:VEVENT
